1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:07,032
THE ADVENTURES OF SHERLOCK HOLMES bySIR ARTHUR CONAN DOYLE

2
00:00:07,032 --> 00:00:10,229
ADVENTURE I.A SCANDAL IN BOHEMIA

3
00:00:10,229 --> 00:00:17,023
I.To Sherlock Holmes she is always THE woman.

4
00:00:17,023 --> 00:00:21,139
I have seldom heard him mention her underany other name.

5
00:00:21,139 --> 00:00:25,689
In his eyes she eclipses and predominatesthe whole of her sex.

6
00:00:25,689 --> 00:00:30,075
It was not that he felt any emotion akin tolove for Irene Adler.

7
00:00:30,075 --> 00:00:36,639
All emotions, and that one particularly,were abhorrent to his cold, precise but

8
00:00:36,639 --> 00:00:38,079
admirably balanced mind.

9
00:00:38,079 --> 00:00:42,819
He was, I take it, the most perfectreasoning and observing machine that the

10
00:00:42,819 --> 00:00:48,009
world has seen, but as a lover he wouldhave placed himself in a false position.

11
00:00:48,009 --> 00:00:53,749
He never spoke of the softer passions, savewith a gibe and a sneer.

12
00:00:53,749 --> 00:00:57,085
They were admirable things for theobserver--excellent for drawing the veil

13
00:00:57,085 --> 00:01:00,013
from men's motives and actions.

14
00:01:00,013 --> 00:01:05,013
But for the trained reasoner to admit suchintrusions into his own delicate and finely

15
00:01:05,013 --> 00:01:10,028
adjusted temperament was to introduce adistracting factor which might throw a

16
00:01:10,028 --> 00:01:13,012
doubt upon all his mental results.

17
00:01:13,012 --> 00:01:18,065
Grit in a sensitive instrument, or a crackin one of his own high-power lenses, would

18
00:01:18,065 --> 00:01:23,049
not be more disturbing than a strongemotion in a nature such as his.

19
00:01:23,049 --> 00:01:29,026
And yet there was but one woman to him, andthat woman was the late Irene Adler, of

20
00:01:29,026 --> 00:01:35,002
dubious and questionable memory.I had seen little of Holmes lately.

21
00:01:35,002 --> 00:01:38,035
My marriage had drifted us away from eachother.

22
00:01:38,035 --> 00:01:43,024
My own complete happiness, and the home-centred interests which rise up around the

23
00:01:43,024 --> 00:01:48,019
man who first finds himself master of hisown establishment, were sufficient to

24
00:01:48,019 --> 00:01:51,084
absorb all my attention, while Holmes, who

25
00:01:51,084 --> 00:01:57,002
loathed every form of society with hiswhole Bohemian soul, remained in our

26
00:01:57,002 --> 00:02:02,051
lodgings in Baker Street, buried among hisold books, and alternating from week to

27
00:02:02,051 --> 00:02:05,052
week between cocaine and ambition, the

28
00:02:05,052 --> 00:02:10,669
drowsiness of the drug, and the fierceenergy of his own keen nature.

29
00:02:10,669 --> 00:02:17,013
He was still, as ever, deeply attracted bythe study of crime, and occupied his

30
00:02:17,013 --> 00:02:22,069
immense faculties and extraordinary powersof observation in following out those

31
00:02:22,069 --> 00:02:25,419
clues, and clearing up those mysteries

32
00:02:25,419 --> 00:02:29,091
which had been abandoned as hopeless by theofficial police.

33
00:02:29,091 --> 00:02:35,089
From time to time I heard some vagueaccount of his doings: of his summons to

34
00:02:35,089 --> 00:02:40,479
Odessa in the case of the Trepoff murder,of his clearing up of the singular tragedy

35
00:02:40,479 --> 00:02:43,099
of the Atkinson brothers at Trincomalee,

36
00:02:43,099 --> 00:02:48,709
and finally of the mission which he hadaccomplished so delicately and successfully

37
00:02:48,709 --> 00:02:50,078
for the reigning family of Holland.

38
00:02:50,078 --> 00:02:56,019
Beyond these signs of his activity,however, which I merely shared with all the

39
00:02:56,019 --> 00:03:02,039
readers of the daily press, I knew littleof my former friend and companion.

40
00:03:02,039 --> 00:03:08,099
One night--it was on the twentieth ofMarch, 1888--I was returning from a journey

41
00:03:08,099 --> 00:03:13,044
to a patient (for I had now returned tocivil practice), when my way led me through

42
00:03:13,044 --> 00:03:14,839
Baker Street.

43
00:03:14,839 --> 00:03:20,052
As I passed the well-remembered door, whichmust always be associated in my mind with

44
00:03:20,052 --> 00:03:26,229
my wooing, and with the dark incidents ofthe Study in Scarlet, I was seized with a

45
00:03:26,229 --> 00:03:29,022
keen desire to see Holmes again, and to

46
00:03:29,022 --> 00:03:32,679
know how he was employing his extraordinarypowers.

47
00:03:32,679 --> 00:03:39,069
His rooms were brilliantly lit, and, evenas I looked up, I saw his tall, spare

48
00:03:39,069 --> 00:03:43,129
figure pass twice in a dark silhouetteagainst the blind.

49
00:03:43,129 --> 00:03:48,649
He was pacing the room swiftly, eagerly,with his head sunk upon his chest and his

50
00:03:48,649 --> 00:03:51,005
hands clasped behind him.

51
00:03:51,005 --> 00:03:56,819
To me, who knew his every mood and habit,his attitude and manner told their own

52
00:03:56,819 --> 00:04:00,047
story.He was at work again.

53
00:04:00,047 --> 00:04:05,014
He had risen out of his drug-created dreamsand was hot upon the scent of some new

54
00:04:05,014 --> 00:04:06,419
problem.

55
00:04:06,419 --> 00:04:11,419
I rang the bell and was shown up to thechamber which had formerly been in part my

56
00:04:11,419 --> 00:04:14,369
own.His manner was not effusive.

57
00:04:14,369 --> 00:04:18,019
It seldom was; but he was glad, I think, tosee me.

58
00:04:18,019 --> 00:04:24,004
With hardly a word spoken, but with akindly eye, he waved me to an armchair,

59
00:04:24,004 --> 00:04:29,058
threw across his case of cigars, andindicated a spirit case and a gasogene in

60
00:04:29,058 --> 00:04:30,091
the corner.

61
00:04:30,091 --> 00:04:37,077
Then he stood before the fire and looked meover in his singular introspective fashion.

62
00:04:37,077 --> 00:04:43,003
"Wedlock suits you," he remarked."I think, Watson, that you have put on

63
00:04:43,003 --> 00:04:46,049
seven and a half pounds since I saw you."

64
00:04:46,049 --> 00:04:49,008
"Seven!"I answered.

65
00:04:49,008 --> 00:04:51,098
"Indeed, I should have thought a littlemore.

66
00:04:51,098 --> 00:04:54,079
Just a trifle more, I fancy, Watson.

67
00:04:54,079 --> 00:04:59,095
And in practice again, I observe.You did not tell me that you intended to go

68
00:04:59,095 --> 00:05:04,003
into harness.""Then, how do you know?"

69
00:05:04,003 --> 00:05:06,076
"I see it, I deduce it.

70
00:05:06,076 --> 00:05:10,099
How do I know that you have been gettingyourself very wet lately, and that you have

71
00:05:10,099 --> 00:05:18,029
a most clumsy and careless servant girl?""My dear Holmes," said I, "this is too

72
00:05:18,029 --> 00:05:19,032
much.

73
00:05:19,032 --> 00:05:24,013
You would certainly have been burned, hadyou lived a few centuries ago.

74
00:05:24,013 --> 00:05:29,091
It is true that I had a country walk onThursday and came home in a dreadful mess,

75
00:05:29,091 --> 00:05:34,091
but as I have changed my clothes I can'timagine how you deduce it.

76
00:05:34,091 --> 00:05:40,032
As to Mary Jane, she is incorrigible, andmy wife has given her notice, but there,

77
00:05:40,032 --> 00:05:47,001
again, I fail to see how you work it out."He chuckled to himself and rubbed his long,

78
00:05:47,001 --> 00:05:49,066
nervous hands together.

79
00:05:49,066 --> 00:05:55,027
"It is simplicity itself," said he; "myeyes tell me that on the inside of your

80
00:05:55,027 --> 00:06:01,026
left shoe, just where the firelight strikesit, the leather is scored by six almost

81
00:06:01,026 --> 00:06:02,092
parallel cuts.

82
00:06:02,092 --> 00:06:07,056
Obviously they have been caused by someonewho has very carelessly scraped round the

83
00:06:07,056 --> 00:06:11,088
edges of the sole in order to removecrusted mud from it.

84
00:06:11,088 --> 00:06:17,036
Hence, you see, my double deduction thatyou had been out in vile weather, and that

85
00:06:17,036 --> 00:06:23,035
you had a particularly malignant boot-slitting specimen of the London slavey.

86
00:06:23,035 --> 00:06:29,022
As to your practice, if a gentleman walksinto my rooms smelling of iodoform, with a

87
00:06:29,022 --> 00:06:34,098
black mark of nitrate of silver upon hisright forefinger, and a bulge on the right

88
00:06:34,098 --> 00:06:37,004
side of his top-hat to show where he has

89
00:06:37,004 --> 00:06:44,022
secreted his stethoscope, I must be dull,indeed, if I do not pronounce him to be an

90
00:06:44,022 --> 00:06:47,006
active member of the medical profession."

91
00:06:47,006 --> 00:06:51,084
I could not help laughing at the ease withwhich he explained his process of

92
00:06:51,084 --> 00:06:52,035
deduction.

93
00:06:52,035 --> 00:06:59,033
"When I hear you give your reasons," Iremarked, "the thing always appears to me

94
00:06:59,033 --> 00:07:05,017
to be so ridiculously simple that I couldeasily do it myself, though at each

95
00:07:05,017 --> 00:07:09,066
successive instance of your reasoning I ambaffled until you explain your process.

96
00:07:09,066 --> 00:07:14,012
And yet I believe that my eyes are as goodas yours."

97
00:07:14,012 --> 00:07:18,098
"Quite so," he answered, lighting acigarette, and throwing himself down into

98
00:07:18,098 --> 00:07:23,047
an armchair."You see, but you do not observe.

99
00:07:23,047 --> 00:07:25,027
The distinction is clear.

100
00:07:25,027 --> 00:07:29,091
For example, you have frequently seen thesteps which lead up from the hall to this

101
00:07:29,091 --> 00:07:32,088
room.""Frequently."

102
00:07:32,088 --> 00:07:34,054
"How often?"

103
00:07:34,054 --> 00:07:41,003
"Well, some hundreds of times.""Then how many are there?"

104
00:07:41,003 --> 00:07:44,003
"How many?I don't know."

105
00:07:44,003 --> 00:07:45,075
"Quite so!

106
00:07:45,075 --> 00:07:49,009
You have not observed.And yet you have seen.

107
00:07:49,009 --> 00:07:54,028
That is just my point.Now, I know that there are seventeen steps,

108
00:07:54,028 --> 00:07:57,024
because I have both seen and observed.

109
00:07:57,024 --> 00:08:01,079
By-the-way, since you are interested inthese little problems, and since you are

110
00:08:01,079 --> 00:08:07,008
good enough to chronicle one or two of mytrifling experiences, you may be interested

111
00:08:07,008 --> 00:08:09,025
in this."

112
00:08:09,025 --> 00:08:13,078
He threw over a sheet of thick, pink-tintednote-paper which had been lying open upon

113
00:08:13,078 --> 00:08:18,041
the table."It came by the last post," said he.

114
00:08:18,041 --> 00:08:20,062
"Read it aloud."

115
00:08:20,062 --> 00:08:26,024
The note was undated, and without eithersignature or address.

116
00:08:26,024 --> 00:08:31,097
"There will call upon you to-night, at aquarter to eight o'clock," it said, "a

117
00:08:31,097 --> 00:08:37,759
gentleman who desires to consult you upon amatter of the very deepest moment.

118
00:08:37,759 --> 00:08:42,269
Your recent services to one of the royalhouses of Europe have shown that you are

119
00:08:42,269 --> 00:08:48,039
one who may safely be trusted with matterswhich are of an importance which can hardly

120
00:08:48,039 --> 00:08:49,849
be exaggerated.

121
00:08:49,849 --> 00:08:53,559
This account of you we have from allquarters received.

122
00:08:53,559 --> 00:08:59,002
Be in your chamber then at that hour, anddo not take it amiss if your visitor wear a

123
00:08:59,002 --> 00:09:00,045
mask."

124
00:09:00,045 --> 00:09:07,879
"This is indeed a mystery," I remarked."What do you imagine that it means?"

125
00:09:07,879 --> 00:09:12,739
"I have no data yet.It is a capital mistake to theorize before

126
00:09:12,739 --> 00:09:14,689
one has data.

127
00:09:14,689 --> 00:09:19,095
Insensibly one begins to twist facts tosuit theories, instead of theories to suit

128
00:09:19,095 --> 00:09:22,739
facts.But the note itself.

129
00:09:22,739 --> 00:09:25,052
What do you deduce from it?"

130
00:09:25,052 --> 00:09:31,299
I carefully examined the writing, and thepaper upon which it was written.

131
00:09:31,299 --> 00:09:37,022
"The man who wrote it was presumably wellto do," I remarked, endeavouring to imitate

132
00:09:37,022 --> 00:09:39,004
my companion's processes.

133
00:09:39,004 --> 00:09:43,239
"Such paper could not be bought under halfa crown a packet.

134
00:09:43,239 --> 00:09:50,027
It is peculiarly strong and stiff.""Peculiar--that is the very word," said

135
00:09:50,027 --> 00:09:51,049
Holmes.

136
00:09:51,049 --> 00:09:55,939
"It is not an English paper at all.Hold it up to the light."

137
00:09:55,939 --> 00:10:04,729
I did so, and saw a large "E" with a small"g," a "P," and a large "G" with a small

138
00:10:04,729 --> 00:10:09,001
"t" woven into the texture of the paper.

139
00:10:09,001 --> 00:10:16,129
"What do you make of that?" asked Holmes."The name of the maker, no doubt; or his

140
00:10:16,129 --> 00:10:18,299
monogram, rather.""Not at all.

141
00:10:18,299 --> 00:10:23,669
The 'G' with the small 't' stands for'Gesellschaft,' which is the German for

142
00:10:23,669 --> 00:10:27,007
'Company.'It is a customary contraction like our

143
00:10:27,007 --> 00:10:29,479
'Co.'

144
00:10:29,479 --> 00:10:34,052
'P,' of course, stands for 'Papier.'Now for the 'Eg.'

145
00:10:34,052 --> 00:10:38,027
Let us glance at our ContinentalGazetteer."

146
00:10:38,027 --> 00:10:41,869
He took down a heavy brown volume from hisshelves.

147
00:10:41,869 --> 00:10:50,179
"Eglow, Eglonitz--here we are, Egria.It is in a German-speaking country--in

148
00:10:50,179 --> 00:10:52,419
Bohemia, not far from Carlsbad.

149
00:10:52,419 --> 00:10:58,489
'Remarkable as being the scene of the deathof Wallenstein, and for its numerous glass-

150
00:10:58,489 --> 00:11:03,989
factories and paper-mills.'Ha, ha, my boy, what do you make of that?"

151
00:11:03,989 --> 00:11:08,039
His eyes sparkled, and he sent up a greatblue triumphant cloud from his cigarette.

152
00:11:08,039 --> 00:11:14,076
"The paper was made in Bohemia," I said."Precisely.

153
00:11:14,076 --> 00:11:18,169
And the man who wrote the note is a German.

154
00:11:18,169 --> 00:11:23,349
Do you note the peculiar construction ofthe sentence--'This account of you we have

155
00:11:23,349 --> 00:11:27,939
from all quarters received.'A Frenchman or Russian could not have

156
00:11:27,939 --> 00:11:29,099
written that.

157
00:11:29,099 --> 00:11:33,007
It is the German who is so uncourteous tohis verbs.

158
00:11:33,007 --> 00:11:37,799
It only remains, therefore, to discoverwhat is wanted by this German who writes

159
00:11:37,799 --> 00:11:43,065
upon Bohemian paper and prefers wearing amask to showing his face.

160
00:11:43,065 --> 00:11:49,859
And here he comes, if I am not mistaken, toresolve all our doubts."

161
00:11:49,859 --> 00:11:53,969
As he spoke there was the sharp sound ofhorses' hoofs and grating wheels against

162
00:11:53,969 --> 00:11:57,659
the curb, followed by a sharp pull at thebell.

163
00:11:57,659 --> 00:11:58,053
Holmes whistled.

164
00:11:58,053 --> 00:12:05,439
"A pair, by the sound," said he."Yes," he continued, glancing out of the

165
00:12:05,439 --> 00:12:08,229
window."A nice little brougham and a pair of

166
00:12:08,229 --> 00:12:09,249
beauties.

167
00:12:09,249 --> 00:12:13,089
A hundred and fifty guineas apiece.There's money in this case, Watson, if

168
00:12:13,089 --> 00:12:19,409
there is nothing else.""I think that I had better go, Holmes."

169
00:12:19,409 --> 00:12:20,096
"Not a bit, Doctor.

170
00:12:20,096 --> 00:12:24,559
Stay where you are.I am lost without my Boswell.

171
00:12:24,559 --> 00:12:29,032
And this promises to be interesting.It would be a pity to miss it."

172
00:12:29,032 --> 00:12:30,939
"But your client--"

173
00:12:30,939 --> 00:12:35,369
"Never mind him.I may want your help, and so may he.

174
00:12:35,369 --> 00:12:38,989
Here he comes.Sit down in that armchair, Doctor, and give

175
00:12:38,989 --> 00:12:40,229
us your best attention."

176
00:12:40,229 --> 00:12:47,739
A slow and heavy step, which had been heardupon the stairs and in the passage, paused

177
00:12:47,739 --> 00:12:52,004
immediately outside the door.Then there was a loud and authoritative

178
00:12:52,004 --> 00:12:53,609
tap.

179
00:12:53,609 --> 00:12:58,083
"Come in!" said Holmes.A man entered who could hardly have been

180
00:12:58,083 --> 00:13:04,008
less than six feet six inches in height,with the chest and limbs of a Hercules.

181
00:13:04,008 --> 00:13:10,008
His dress was rich with a richness whichwould, in England, be looked upon as akin

182
00:13:10,008 --> 00:13:12,289
to bad taste.

183
00:13:12,289 --> 00:13:16,719
Heavy bands of astrakhan were slashedacross the sleeves and fronts of his

184
00:13:16,719 --> 00:13:21,052
double-breasted coat, while the deep bluecloak which was thrown over his shoulders

185
00:13:21,052 --> 00:13:24,359
was lined with flame-coloured silk and

186
00:13:24,359 --> 00:13:29,919
secured at the neck with a brooch whichconsisted of a single flaming beryl.

187
00:13:29,919 --> 00:13:34,679
Boots which extended halfway up his calves,and which were trimmed at the tops with

188
00:13:34,679 --> 00:13:40,489
rich brown fur, completed the impression ofbarbaric opulence which was suggested by

189
00:13:40,489 --> 00:13:42,034
his whole appearance.

190
00:13:42,034 --> 00:13:47,659
He carried a broad-brimmed hat in his hand,while he wore across the upper part of his

191
00:13:47,659 --> 00:13:54,029
face, extending down past the cheekbones, ablack vizard mask, which he had apparently

192
00:13:54,029 --> 00:13:59,034
adjusted that very moment, for his hand wasstill raised to it as he entered.

193
00:13:59,034 --> 00:14:04,119
From the lower part of the face he appearedto be a man of strong character, with a

194
00:14:04,119 --> 00:14:09,096
thick, hanging lip, and a long, straightchin suggestive of resolution pushed to the

195
00:14:09,096 --> 00:14:12,799
length of obstinacy.

196
00:14:12,799 --> 00:14:18,051
"You had my note?" he asked with a deepharsh voice and a strongly marked German

197
00:14:18,051 --> 00:14:22,083
accent."I told you that I would call."

198
00:14:22,083 --> 00:14:28,077
He looked from one to the other of us, asif uncertain which to address.

199
00:14:28,077 --> 00:14:31,499
"Pray take a seat," said Holmes.

200
00:14:31,499 --> 00:14:36,489
"This is my friend and colleague, Dr.Watson, who is occasionally good enough to

201
00:14:36,489 --> 00:14:41,051
help me in my cases.Whom have I the honour to address?"

202
00:14:41,051 --> 00:14:46,779
"You may address me as the Count Von Kramm,a Bohemian nobleman.

203
00:14:46,779 --> 00:14:53,014
I understand that this gentleman, yourfriend, is a man of honour and discretion,

204
00:14:53,014 --> 00:14:57,559
whom I may trust with a matter of the mostextreme importance.

205
00:14:57,559 --> 00:15:02,219
If not, I should much prefer to communicatewith you alone."

206
00:15:02,219 --> 00:15:08,059
I rose to go, but Holmes caught me by thewrist and pushed me back into my chair.

207
00:15:08,059 --> 00:15:11,669
"It is both, or none," said he.

208
00:15:11,669 --> 00:15:16,279
"You may say before this gentleman anythingwhich you may say to me."

209
00:15:16,279 --> 00:15:18,033
The Count shrugged his broad shoulders.

210
00:15:18,033 --> 00:15:26,929
"Then I must begin," said he, "by bindingyou both to absolute secrecy for two years;

211
00:15:26,929 --> 00:15:31,879
at the end of that time the matter will beof no importance.

212
00:15:31,879 --> 00:15:37,239
At present it is not too much to say thatit is of such weight it may have an

213
00:15:37,239 --> 00:15:44,109
influence upon European history.""I promise," said Holmes.

214
00:15:44,109 --> 00:15:45,979
"And I."

215
00:15:45,979 --> 00:15:50,799
"You will excuse this mask," continued ourstrange visitor.

216
00:15:50,799 --> 00:15:56,077
"The august person who employs me wisheshis agent to be unknown to you, and I may

217
00:15:56,077 --> 00:16:02,099
confess at once that the title by which Ihave just called myself is not exactly my

218
00:16:02,099 --> 00:16:02,014
own."

219
00:16:02,014 --> 00:16:07,369
"I was aware of it," said Holmes dryly.

220
00:16:07,369 --> 00:16:13,539
"The circumstances are of great delicacy,and every precaution has to be taken to

221
00:16:13,539 --> 00:16:19,469
quench what might grow to be an immensescandal and seriously compromise one of the

222
00:16:19,469 --> 00:16:21,669
reigning families of Europe.

223
00:16:21,669 --> 00:16:28,008
To speak plainly, the matter implicates thegreat House of Ormstein, hereditary kings

224
00:16:28,008 --> 00:16:30,004
of Bohemia."

225
00:16:30,004 --> 00:16:35,439
"I was also aware of that," murmuredHolmes, settling himself down in his

226
00:16:35,439 --> 00:16:38,229
armchair and closing his eyes.

227
00:16:38,229 --> 00:16:43,089
Our visitor glanced with some apparentsurprise at the languid, lounging figure of

228
00:16:43,089 --> 00:16:48,629
the man who had been no doubt depicted tohim as the most incisive reasoner and most

229
00:16:48,629 --> 00:16:51,027
energetic agent in Europe.

230
00:16:51,027 --> 00:16:57,849
Holmes slowly reopened his eyes and lookedimpatiently at his gigantic client.

231
00:16:57,849 --> 00:17:03,909
"If your Majesty would condescend to stateyour case," he remarked, "I should be

232
00:17:03,909 --> 00:17:06,083
better able to advise you."

233
00:17:06,083 --> 00:17:11,024
The man sprang from his chair and paced upand down the room in uncontrollable

234
00:17:11,024 --> 00:17:12,058
agitation.

235
00:17:12,058 --> 00:17:16,909
Then, with a gesture of desperation, hetore the mask from his face and hurled it

236
00:17:16,909 --> 00:17:21,679
upon the ground."You are right," he cried; "I am the King.

237
00:17:21,679 --> 00:17:25,549
Why should I attempt to conceal it?"

238
00:17:25,549 --> 00:17:28,249
"Why, indeed?" murmured Holmes.

239
00:17:28,249 --> 00:17:33,529
"Your Majesty had not spoken before I wasaware that I was addressing Wilhelm

240
00:17:33,529 --> 00:17:40,259
Gottsreich Sigismond von Ormstein, GrandDuke of Cassel-Felstein, and hereditary

241
00:17:40,259 --> 00:17:41,007
King of Bohemia."

242
00:17:41,007 --> 00:17:48,004
"But you can understand," said our strangevisitor, sitting down once more and passing

243
00:17:48,004 --> 00:17:54,159
his hand over his high white forehead, "youcan understand that I am not accustomed to

244
00:17:54,159 --> 00:17:56,069
doing such business in my own person.

245
00:17:56,069 --> 00:18:01,869
Yet the matter was so delicate that I couldnot confide it to an agent without putting

246
00:18:01,869 --> 00:18:06,529
myself in his power.I have come incognito from Prague for the

247
00:18:06,529 --> 00:18:09,046
purpose of consulting you."

248
00:18:09,046 --> 00:18:15,369
"Then, pray consult," said Holmes, shuttinghis eyes once more.

249
00:18:15,369 --> 00:18:21,379
"The facts are briefly these: Some fiveyears ago, during a lengthy visit to

250
00:18:21,379 --> 00:18:27,008
Warsaw, I made the acquaintance of thewell-known adventuress, Irene Adler.

251
00:18:27,008 --> 00:18:31,098
The name is no doubt familiar to you."

252
00:18:31,098 --> 00:18:37,084
