324
00:23:14,033 --> 00:23:19,072
"Then, as to money?""You have carte blanche."

325
00:23:19,072 --> 00:23:20,989
"Absolutely?"

326
00:23:20,989 --> 00:23:27,033
"I tell you that I would give one of theprovinces of my kingdom to have that

327
00:23:27,033 --> 00:23:30,509
photograph.""And for present expenses?"

328
00:23:30,509 --> 00:23:34,759
The King took a heavy chamois leather bagfrom under his cloak and laid it on the

329
00:23:34,759 --> 00:23:39,002
table."There are three hundred pounds in gold and

330
00:23:39,002 --> 00:23:41,999
seven hundred in notes," he said.

331
00:23:41,999 --> 00:23:47,007
Holmes scribbled a receipt upon a sheet ofhis note-book and handed it to him.

332
00:23:47,007 --> 00:23:54,095
"And Mademoiselle's address?" he asked."Is Briony Lodge, Serpentine Avenue, St.

333
00:23:54,095 --> 00:23:57,022
John's Wood."

334
00:23:57,022 --> 00:24:02,239
Holmes took a note of it."One other question," said he.

335
00:24:02,239 --> 00:24:07,109
"Was the photograph a cabinet?""It was."

336
00:24:07,109 --> 00:24:11,067
"Then, good-night, your Majesty, and Itrust that we shall soon have some good

337
00:24:11,067 --> 00:24:13,019
news for you.

338
00:24:13,019 --> 00:24:18,002
And good-night, Watson," he added, as thewheels of the royal brougham rolled down

339
00:24:18,002 --> 00:24:19,529
the street.

340
00:24:19,529 --> 00:24:24,239
"If you will be good enough to call to-morrow afternoon at three o'clock I should

341
00:24:24,239 --> 00:24:26,609
like to chat this little matter over withyou."

342
00:24:26,609 --> 00:24:34,739
II.At three o'clock precisely I was at Baker

343
00:24:34,739 --> 00:24:37,879
Street, but Holmes had not yet returned.

344
00:24:37,879 --> 00:24:42,119
The landlady informed me that he had leftthe house shortly after eight o'clock in

345
00:24:42,119 --> 00:24:43,239
the morning.

346
00:24:43,239 --> 00:24:48,379
I sat down beside the fire, however, withthe intention of awaiting him, however long

347
00:24:48,379 --> 00:24:48,899
he might be.

348
00:24:48,899 --> 00:24:54,058
I was already deeply interested in hisinquiry, for, though it was surrounded by

349
00:24:54,058 --> 00:24:59,489
none of the grim and strange features whichwere associated with the two crimes which I

350
00:24:59,489 --> 00:25:02,859
have already recorded, still, the nature of

351
00:25:02,859 --> 00:25:08,045
the case and the exalted station of hisclient gave it a character of its own.

352
00:25:08,045 --> 00:25:13,096
Indeed, apart from the nature of theinvestigation which my friend had on hand,

353
00:25:13,096 --> 00:25:20,159
there was something in his masterly graspof a situation, and his keen, incisive

354
00:25:20,159 --> 00:25:22,019
reasoning, which made it a pleasure to me

355
00:25:22,019 --> 00:25:27,057
to study his system of work, and to followthe quick, subtle methods by which he

356
00:25:27,057 --> 00:25:31,369
disentangled the most inextricablemysteries.

357
00:25:31,369 --> 00:25:36,259
So accustomed was I to his invariablesuccess that the very possibility of his

358
00:25:36,259 --> 00:25:39,989
failing had ceased to enter into my head.

359
00:25:39,989 --> 00:25:45,279
It was close upon four before the dooropened, and a drunken-looking groom, ill-

360
00:25:45,279 --> 00:25:51,009
kempt and side-whiskered, with an inflamedface and disreputable clothes, walked into

361
00:25:51,009 --> 00:25:52,609
the room.

362
00:25:52,609 --> 00:25:58,639
Accustomed as I was to my friend's amazingpowers in the use of disguises, I had to

363
00:25:58,639 --> 00:26:03,259
look three times before I was certain thatit was indeed he.

364
00:26:03,259 --> 00:26:07,097
With a nod he vanished into the bedroom,whence he emerged in five minutes tweed-

365
00:26:07,097 --> 00:26:11,003
suited and respectable, as of old.

366
00:26:11,003 --> 00:26:15,056
Putting his hands into his pockets, hestretched out his legs in front of the fire

367
00:26:15,056 --> 00:26:18,082
and laughed heartily for some minutes.

368
00:26:18,082 --> 00:26:24,129
"Well, really!" he cried, and then hechoked and laughed again until he was

369
00:26:24,129 --> 00:26:28,989
obliged to lie back, limp and helpless, inthe chair.

370
00:26:28,989 --> 00:26:29,379
"What is it?"

371
00:26:29,379 --> 00:26:35,369
"It's quite too funny.I am sure you could never guess how I

372
00:26:35,369 --> 00:26:39,059
employed my morning, or what I ended bydoing."

373
00:26:39,059 --> 00:26:41,519
"I can't imagine.

374
00:26:41,519 --> 00:26:47,017
I suppose that you have been watching thehabits, and perhaps the house, of Miss

375
00:26:47,017 --> 00:26:50,084
Irene Adler.""Quite so; but the sequel was rather

376
00:26:50,084 --> 00:26:52,259
unusual.

377
00:26:52,259 --> 00:26:56,379
I will tell you, however.I left the house a little after eight

378
00:26:56,379 --> 00:27:00,034
o'clock this morning in the character of agroom out of work.

379
00:27:00,034 --> 00:27:04,759
There is a wonderful sympathy andfreemasonry among horsey men.

380
00:27:04,759 --> 00:27:09,019
Be one of them, and you will know all thatthere is to know.

381
00:27:09,019 --> 00:27:11,083
I soon found Briony Lodge.

382
00:27:11,083 --> 00:27:16,008
It is a bijou villa, with a garden at theback, but built out in front right up to

383
00:27:16,008 --> 00:27:20,081
the road, two stories.Chubb lock to the door.

384
00:27:20,081 --> 00:27:26,109
Large sitting-room on the right side, wellfurnished, with long windows almost to the

385
00:27:26,109 --> 00:27:32,031
floor, and those preposterous Englishwindow fasteners which a child could open.

386
00:27:32,031 --> 00:27:36,389
Behind there was nothing remarkable, savethat the passage window could be reached

387
00:27:36,389 --> 00:27:38,739
from the top of the coach-house.

388
00:27:38,739 --> 00:27:43,659
I walked round it and examined it closelyfrom every point of view, but without

389
00:27:43,659 --> 00:27:46,889
noting anything else of interest.

390
00:27:46,889 --> 00:27:52,084
"I then lounged down the street and found,as I expected, that there was a mews in a

391
00:27:52,084 --> 00:27:56,002
lane which runs down by one wall of thegarden.

392
00:27:56,002 --> 00:28:01,409
I lent the ostlers a hand in rubbing downtheir horses, and received in exchange

393
00:28:01,409 --> 00:28:06,097
twopence, a glass of half and half, twofills of shag tobacco, and as much

394
00:28:06,097 --> 00:28:09,489
information as I could desire about Miss

395
00:28:09,489 --> 00:28:14,044
Adler, to say nothing of half a dozen otherpeople in the neighbourhood in whom I was

396
00:28:14,044 --> 00:28:20,609
not in the least interested, but whosebiographies I was compelled to listen to."

397
00:28:20,609 --> 00:28:22,529
"And what of Irene Adler?"

398
00:28:22,529 --> 00:28:26,649
I asked."Oh, she has turned all the men's heads

399
00:28:26,649 --> 00:28:30,609
down in that part.She is the daintiest thing under a bonnet

400
00:28:30,609 --> 00:28:32,005
on this planet.

401
00:28:32,005 --> 00:28:38,083
So say the Serpentine-mews, to a man.She lives quietly, sings at concerts,

402
00:28:38,083 --> 00:28:43,869
drives out at five every day, and returnsat seven sharp for dinner.

403
00:28:43,869 --> 00:28:47,043
Seldom goes out at other times, except whenshe sings.

404
00:28:47,043 --> 00:28:51,009
Has only one male visitor, but a good dealof him.

405
00:28:51,009 --> 00:28:56,056
He is dark, handsome, and dashing, nevercalls less than once a day, and often

406
00:28:56,056 --> 00:29:00,989
twice.He is a Mr. Godfrey Norton, of the Inner

407
00:29:00,989 --> 00:29:02,759
Temple.

408
00:29:02,759 --> 00:29:06,047
See the advantages of a cabman as aconfidant.

409
00:29:06,047 --> 00:29:12,056
They had driven him home a dozen times fromSerpentine-mews, and knew all about him.

410
00:29:12,056 --> 00:29:16,979
When I had listened to all they had totell, I began to walk up and down near

411
00:29:16,979 --> 00:29:22,046
Briony Lodge once more, and to think overmy plan of campaign.

412
00:29:22,046 --> 00:29:27,629
"This Godfrey Norton was evidently animportant factor in the matter.

413
00:29:27,629 --> 00:29:31,249
